    "body": "### Problem\n\nThere is no `TermResponse` event triggered in response to a manual `io.stdout:write('\\027]11;?\\007')` after a `:restart`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create the following 'init.lua':\n\n    ```lua\n    _G.log = {}\n    local f = function(ev) table.insert(_G.log, vim.deepcopy(ev)) end\n    vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('TermResponse', { callback = f, nested = true })\n    -- Detect the terminal background color\n    io.stdout:write('\\027]11;?\\007')\n    ```\n\n2. `nvim --clean -u init.lua`\n3. `:=log` shows two entries: one as a response to `\\027]11;?\\007` (with `data.sequence` like `\"\\27]11;rgb:0808/1818/2323\"`) followed by something else (in my case one entry with a `data.sequence` like `\"\\27[?62;22;52c\"`).\n4. `:restart`\n5. `:=log` shows only the second entry (even after waiting couple of seconds).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`:restart` works as if manually `:qall` followed by opening `nvim` again. In this particular case, the `TermResponse` event should trigger in response to an explicit manual `io.stdout:write('\\027]11;?\\007')` during startup.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nBoth 0.12.0 and NVIM v0.13.0-dev-68+gb64d96ed8d\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, doesn't have this functionality\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nEndeavourOS Linux x86_64, 6.19.10-arch1-1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.3.1-arch1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nAppimage and built from source",
